04162nam a22005895i 9780804790604DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202014cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047906047 a10.1515/97808047906042doi  a(DE-B1597)564839  a(OCoLC)1198930092  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aCT788.H275bM35 2014 7aBIO0000002bisacsh04a942.06092aB2231 aMalay, Jessica, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Case of Mistress Mary Hampson :bHer Story of Marital Abuse and Defiance in Seventeenth-Century England /cJessica Malay. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tacknowledgments -- tA chronology of the life of Mary Hampson -- tIntroduction: Early Modern Marriage and the Case of Mrs. Mary Hampson -- tA Plain and Compendious Relation of the Case of Mrs. Mary Hampson...(London, 1684) -- t1. The Hampson Marriage: Competing Stories -- t2. Afterlife of a Marriage: Accusations and Recriminations -- t3. The Widow Hampson and Her Daughters -- tConclusions -- tAppendix: Letters from Mary Hampson to William Trumbull (1680-1681) -- tNotes -- tSuggested Reading 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe centerpiece of The Case of Mistress Mary Hampson is the autobiographical narrative of a 17th-century woman in an abusive and violent marriage. Composed at a time when marital disharmony was in vogue with readers and publishers, it stands out from comparable works, usually single broadsheets. In her own words, Mary recounts various dramatic and stressful episodes from her decades-long marriage to Robert Hampson and her strategies for dealing with it. The harrowing tale contains scenes of physical abuse, mob violence, abandonment, flight, and destitution. It also shows moments of personal courage and interventions on the author's behalf by friends and strangers, some of whom are subject to severe reprisals. Mary wrote her story to come to terms with her situation, to justify her actions, and to cast herself in a virtuous light. The accompanying discussion of her life, drawn from other sources, provides chilling evidence of the vulnerability of seventeenth-century women and the flawed legal mechanisms that were supposed to protect them. Readers are also invited to consider in what ways the self-portrait is accurate and what elements of it may be considered fabrication. Malay's archival efforts have thus rescued a compelling and complicated voice from the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAbused wiveszEnglandvBiography. 0aMarriagezEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aWife abusezEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 4aautobiography. 4aearly modern family. 4aearly modern legal system. 4aearly modern marriage. 4amarital abuse. 4aseventeenth-century pamphlets. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479060440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804790604423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804790604.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles